Andrew seems to think thathis mother was murdered.

277
00:20:04,420 --> 00:20:07,641
I thought I told younot to mention his mother.

278
00:20:07,771 --> 00:20:08,816
You did.

279
00:20:08,946 --> 00:20:11,819
I'm sorry.

280
00:20:11,949 --> 00:20:14,517
I suppose his
grandparents told him.

281
00:20:14,648 --> 00:20:16,258
They despised me.

282
00:20:16,389 --> 00:20:17,128
Why?

283
00:20:21,742 --> 00:20:23,004
Because they
believe that I did it.

284
00:20:27,922 --> 00:20:31,621
Why did Andy go to live
with his grandparents?

285
00:20:31,752 --> 00:20:32,927
Because they wanted
him, and I didn't.

286
00:20:33,057 --> 00:20:36,060
It was as simple as that.

287
00:20:36,191 --> 00:20:38,802
Until they capsized
their sailboat, and then

288
00:20:38,933 --> 00:20:39,803
I had to have him.

289
00:20:44,155 --> 00:20:45,505
How do you feel about him now?

290
00:20:49,509 --> 00:20:52,207
If you'll excuse me,
I'd like some privacy.

291
00:20:52,338 --> 00:20:55,123
I have a lot of reading to do.

292
00:20:55,254 --> 00:20:57,778
Of course.

293
00:20:57,908 --> 00:20:59,214
Good night.

294
00:20:59,345 --> 00:21:00,128
Good night.

295
00:21:03,740 --> 00:21:07,091
[music playing]

296
00:21:28,069 --> 00:21:29,418
[knocking on door]

297
00:21:32,029 --> 00:21:33,379
I'm sorry.

298
00:22:14,811 --> 00:22:16,465
Ms. Guinness.

299
00:22:16,596 --> 00:22:17,336
Don't worry.

300
00:22:17,466 --> 00:22:18,467
I don't kill nannies.

301
00:22:22,950 --> 00:22:23,777
[slams door]

302
00:22:30,827 --> 00:22:35,266
Andy, would you take
this up to your father?

303
00:22:35,397 --> 00:22:37,051
- No.
- Well, please.

304
00:22:37,181 --> 00:22:39,053
You're going that way.

305
00:22:39,183 --> 00:22:40,228
I don't want to disturb him.

306
00:22:40,359 --> 00:22:41,621
Well Andy, he has to eat.

307
00:22:41,751 --> 00:22:44,406
Please.

308
00:22:44,537 --> 00:22:45,842
Oh, all right.

309
00:22:45,973 --> 00:22:46,800
Thank you.

310
00:22:46,930 --> 00:22:47,670
Can you manage?

311
00:22:47,801 --> 00:22:48,541
Yes.

312
00:22:52,371 --> 00:22:55,635
Why did Alycia's parents tellAndy his mother was murdered?

313
00:22:55,765 --> 00:23:00,030
They never accepted that Mrs.Keaton could take her own life.

314
00:23:00,161 --> 00:23:04,165
Didn't they understandwhat it could do to Andy?

315
00:23:04,295 --> 00:23:07,560
[music playing]

316
00:23:21,574 --> 00:23:22,923
[knocking on door]

317
00:23:29,016 --> 00:23:29,799
Yes, Andrew.

318
00:23:29,930 --> 00:23:30,844
What is it?

319
00:23:30,974 --> 00:23:33,237
Welcome home.

320
00:23:33,368 --> 00:23:34,413
I brought you breakfast.

321
00:23:38,939 --> 00:23:42,725
Thank you.

322
00:23:42,856 --> 00:23:45,075
Look, I'm real busy right now.

323
00:23:45,206 --> 00:23:46,337
We'll talk later, OK?

324
00:23:46,468 --> 00:23:49,558
I'll come down for dinner.

325
00:23:49,689 --> 00:23:50,429
Yes, father.

326
00:23:57,305 --> 00:23:58,785
Uh-oh.

327
00:23:58,915 --> 00:24:03,224
They don't sound
like very happy feet.

328
00:24:03,354 --> 00:24:08,142
Andy, what happened?
What happened?

329
00:24:08,272 --> 00:24:11,101
It's all your fault.
You made me go up there.

330
00:24:11,232 --> 00:24:12,276
I knew I shouldn't have.

331
00:24:12,407 --> 00:24:15,802
I was right about you.

332
00:24:15,932 --> 00:24:16,759
[slams door]

333
00:24:33,863 --> 00:24:35,778
What on earth happened?

334
00:24:35,909 --> 00:24:38,694
Andy is crying his
eyes out downstairs.

335
00:24:38,825 --> 00:24:40,261
Now you've been
gone for two weeks.

336
00:24:40,391 --> 00:24:42,785
Can't you give him a
moment of your time?

337
00:24:42,916 --> 00:24:44,221
Does this constitute
an emergency?

338
00:24:44,352 --> 00:24:46,659
Is there some kind of problem?

339
00:24:46,789 --> 00:24:49,618
Well yes, I think
there is a problem.

340
00:24:49,749 --> 00:24:53,622
Your son Andrew thinks
his mother is a ghost.

341
00:24:53,753 --> 00:24:56,886
Now I can't bring him backfrom that without your help.

342
00:24:57,017 --> 00:24:59,149
If you can't accept theterms of your engagement,

343
00:24:59,280 --> 00:25:02,283
you are free to leave.

344
00:25:02,413 --> 00:25:04,024
I don't understand you.

345
00:25:04,154 --> 00:25:10,160
Ms. Guinness, do you know whatI do if I reach a conclusion

346
00:25:10,291 --> 00:25:13,250
that doesn't make any sense?

347
00:25:13,381 --> 00:25:15,035
I re-examine my premises.

348
00:25:15,165 --> 00:25:18,691
He's not a problem in physics.He's a little boy.

349
00:25:22,216 --> 00:25:24,261
What has made you so-called?

350
00:25:24,392 --> 00:25:26,046
A ghost, Ms. Guinness.

351
00:25:29,179 --> 00:25:30,006
[slams door]

352
00:25:32,661 --> 00:25:35,011
A ghost.

353
00:25:35,142 --> 00:25:38,493
[music playing]

354
00:25:55,075 --> 00:25:56,424
[neighs]

355
00:26:01,603 --> 00:26:02,778
But I thought
you hated horses.

356
00:26:11,961 --> 00:26:13,093
Hello.

357
00:26:13,223 --> 00:26:15,530
Oh, he's beautiful.

358
00:26:15,661 --> 00:26:16,662
What's his name?

359
00:26:16,792 --> 00:26:19,316
Her name is Amber.

360
00:26:19,447 --> 00:26:21,449
She was my mother's favorite.

361
00:26:21,580 --> 00:26:22,929
Have you ever ridden her?

362
00:26:23,059 --> 00:26:24,147
No.

363
00:26:24,278 --> 00:26:25,845
Well you know, I love to ride.

364
00:26:25,975 --> 00:26:28,021
So maybe we could
go out some time.

365
00:26:28,151 --> 00:26:31,938
120 Americans were renderedquadriplegic last year.

366
00:26:32,068 --> 00:26:35,768
There were 18 fatalities.

367
00:26:35,898 --> 00:26:38,118
Is that a yes or no?

368
00:26:38,248 --> 00:26:39,728
You ride her.

369
00:26:39,859 --> 00:26:41,164
[honking]

370
00:26:41,295 --> 00:26:42,122
There's uncle Blain!

371
00:26:52,088 --> 00:26:52,872
Blain, Jilly!

372
00:27:01,881 --> 00:27:04,013
US genuine army surplus.

373
00:27:04,144 --> 00:27:06,625
Picked them up in a
junk shop in Barbados.

374
00:27:06,755 --> 00:27:07,843
They work.

375
00:27:07,974 --> 00:27:08,888
I think they'll
need some fiddling,

376
00:27:09,018 --> 00:27:10,933
but I thought you'd like them.

377
00:27:11,064 --> 00:27:13,196
Your father and I had thesame pair when we were kids.

378
00:27:13,327 --> 00:27:14,589
Of course, Richard
took them apart

379
00:27:14,720 --> 00:27:16,373
and we never could get
them to work again.

380
00:27:16,504 --> 00:27:17,418
They're great.

381
00:27:17,548 --> 00:27:19,202
Thanks, uncle Blain.

382
00:27:19,333 --> 00:27:20,116
They're terrific.

383
00:27:23,511 --> 00:27:25,295
Hi.

384
00:27:25,426 --> 00:27:26,862
Well hello.

385
00:27:26,993 --> 00:27:29,691
Blain Keaton, official
family black sheep.

386
00:27:29,822 --> 00:27:30,866
This is Jillian Zale, my friend.

387
00:27:30,997 --> 00:27:32,041
Hi.

388
00:27:32,172 --> 00:27:32,912
Care for a drink
while I'm pouring?

389
00:27:33,042 --> 00:27:34,870
Oh, no thank you.

390
00:27:35,001 --> 00:27:36,045
I'm Liz Guinness.

391
00:27:36,176 --> 00:27:36,916
I'm Andy's--

392
00:27:37,046 --> 00:27:38,134
She's my new nanny.

393
00:27:38,265 --> 00:27:39,396
Well, my brother's
taste in nannies

394
00:27:39,527 --> 00:27:42,573
has definitely improved.

395
00:27:42,704 --> 00:27:43,705
What are they, Andy?

396
00:27:43,836 --> 00:27:45,402
Walkie-talkies.

397
00:27:45,533 --> 00:27:47,753
If I replace the inductioncoils in the modulator circuits,

398
00:27:47,883 --> 00:27:50,146
they should be effective
anywhere in the house.

399
00:27:50,277 --> 00:27:51,757
So where is the famous man?

400
00:27:51,887 --> 00:27:53,846
He's up in his office working.

401
00:27:53,976 --> 00:27:55,935
Should I send word
that you're here?

402
00:27:56,065 --> 00:27:58,502
My dear girl, he knew wewere here before you did.

403
00:27:58,633 --> 00:28:00,243
Hi.

404
00:28:00,374 --> 00:28:01,984
What a nice surprise, Jillian.

405
00:28:02,115 --> 00:28:04,030
I thought you were going tospend the summer at the Cape.

406
00:28:04,160 --> 00:28:06,380
Oh, Richard.

407
00:28:06,510 --> 00:28:08,034
How could I stay away from you?

408
00:28:12,516 --> 00:28:15,737
Blain.

409
00:28:15,868 --> 00:28:18,392
Richard.

410
00:28:18,522 --> 00:28:21,047
Oh, it's great to be
back in the country.

411
00:28:21,177 --> 00:28:23,527
I'm so sick of the city.

412
00:28:23,658 --> 00:28:25,791
I have a hankering toride your horses, Richard.

413
00:28:25,921 --> 00:28:26,748
Well please do, Jillian.

414
00:28:26,879 --> 00:28:27,923
They could use it.

415
00:28:28,054 --> 00:28:29,882
I've not had time
to ride lately.

416
00:28:30,012 --> 00:28:31,057
Why don't we go
tomorrow morning?

417
00:28:31,187 --> 00:28:32,319
I can't.

418
00:28:32,449 --> 00:28:33,363
My publisher will
kill me if I don't

419
00:28:33,494 --> 00:28:34,495
finish my manuscript on time.

420
00:28:34,625 --> 00:28:35,801
Oh, you're a writer.

421
00:28:35,931 --> 00:28:37,411
And I am his muse.

422
00:28:37,541 --> 00:28:40,327
Isn't that right, Blain?

423
00:28:40,457 --> 00:28:42,851
I must say I was surprised tosee how happy Andrew was today.

424
00:28:42,982 --> 00:28:45,898
Big change from the
last time I saw him.

425
00:28:46,028 --> 00:28:48,291
Well, we have Ms.Guinness to thank for that.

426
00:28:48,422 --> 00:28:50,163
She's working wonders with him.

427
00:28:50,293 --> 00:28:52,774
Well she certainly is a stepup in the nanny department.

428
00:28:52,905 --> 00:28:55,124
Makes me wish I
were eight again.

429
00:28:55,255 --> 00:28:56,691
Still, better late than never.

430
00:29:03,350 --> 00:29:06,788
If you'll excuse me,it's been a very long day.

431
00:29:06,919 --> 00:29:09,704
Andy gets up very early.

432
00:29:09,835 --> 00:29:10,661
Good night.

433
00:29:23,065 --> 00:29:24,240
Liz?

434
00:29:24,371 --> 00:29:27,287
Liz.

435
00:29:27,417 --> 00:29:29,202
Are you really going to bed,or were you just choking

436
00:29:29,332 --> 00:29:31,595
on the tension in there?

437
00:29:31,726 --> 00:29:34,033
They don't like eachother very much, do they?

438
00:29:34,163 --> 00:29:37,253
That's theunderstatement of the year.

439
00:29:37,384 --> 00:29:40,953
How about you and
I having a drink?

440
00:29:41,083 --> 00:29:43,433
OK.

441
00:29:43,564 --> 00:29:44,347
OK.

442
00:29:44,478 --> 00:29:46,872
Come on.

443
00:29:47,002 --> 00:29:50,266
How long are you
staying for this time?

444
00:29:50,397 --> 00:29:53,704
Long enough to
finish my manuscript.

445
00:29:53,835 --> 00:29:56,185
Fine.

446
00:29:56,316 --> 00:29:58,405
Then just keep out of my way.

447
00:29:58,535 --> 00:30:01,234
Richard, I want
to sell the estate.

448
00:30:01,364 --> 00:30:04,019
I've told you just give metime, and I will buy you out.

449
00:30:04,150 --> 00:30:05,412
I'm not prepared
to wait that long.

450
00:30:05,542 --> 00:30:06,326
I want to sell it now.

451
00:30:06,456 --> 00:30:08,328
Oh, don't be so absurd.

452
00:30:08,458 --> 00:30:10,330
This house was built by ourgreat-great-grandfather,

453
00:30:10,460 --> 00:30:11,984
if you hadn't forgotten.

454
00:30:12,114 --> 00:30:14,508
No, I haven't forgotten,as much as I would like to.

455
00:30:14,638 --> 00:30:16,205
Do you really think this
is an appropriate place

456
00:30:16,336 --> 00:30:18,947
for Andy to grow up in?
- Oh no, Blain.

457
00:30:19,078 --> 00:30:22,081
Don't question what
I do for Andrew.

458
00:30:22,211 --> 00:30:23,778
Your rules, your house.

459
00:30:23,909 --> 00:30:25,084
Everything's got to be your way.

460
00:30:25,214 --> 00:30:27,738
You're damn right.

461
00:30:27,869 --> 00:30:30,089
No wonder Alycia
was so unhappy.

462
00:30:30,219 --> 00:30:33,048
How dare you.

463
00:30:33,179 --> 00:30:34,658
You know, I'd have
thought you to be

464
00:30:34,789 --> 00:30:36,835
ashamed to show your face.

465
00:30:36,965 --> 00:30:38,924
I have nothing
to be ashamed of.

466
00:30:39,054 --> 00:30:40,534
Don't mind Blain.

467
00:30:40,664 --> 00:30:42,492
No one else does.

468
00:30:42,623 --> 00:30:45,365
He's not very subtle, is he?

469
00:30:45,495 --> 00:30:47,584
He just can't imagine
a man and a woman

470
00:30:47,715 --> 00:30:49,543
being alone in a place
like this and not

471
00:30:49,673 --> 00:30:53,068
actually sleeping together.

472
00:30:53,199 --> 00:30:56,855
So are you sleeping
with Richard?

473
00:30:56,985 --> 00:30:58,639
No.

474
00:30:58,769 --> 00:31:00,032
I'm sorry.

475
00:31:00,162 --> 00:31:02,817
Blain must be rubbing off on me.

476
00:31:02,948 --> 00:31:04,253
Cheers.

477
00:31:04,384 --> 00:31:05,124
Cheers.

478
00:31:08,040 --> 00:31:10,216
So you like to ride?

479
00:31:10,346 --> 00:31:11,478
Oh, yes.

480
00:31:11,608 --> 00:31:12,609
Especially these horses.

481
00:31:12,740 --> 00:31:14,133
They're so good.
Do you ride?

482
00:31:14,263 --> 00:31:15,047
Mhmm.

483
00:31:15,177 --> 00:31:16,396
I grew up with horses.

484
00:31:16,526 --> 00:31:17,788
Really?

485
00:31:17,919 --> 00:31:19,051
Well we'll have to
ride together sometime.

486
00:31:19,181 --> 00:31:20,835
I'd like that.

487
00:31:20,966 --> 00:31:23,142
I don't understand why
Dr. Keaton keeps them.

488
00:31:23,272 --> 00:31:26,362
I mean, he never goes near them.

489
00:31:26,493 --> 00:31:29,844
Alycia loved them, andthey're part of the museum.

490
00:31:33,543 --> 00:31:36,503
It must have been very
difficult for Dr. Keaton

491
00:31:36,633 --> 00:31:37,634
after she died.

492
00:31:37,765 --> 00:31:40,246
Depends on what you mean.

493
00:31:40,376 --> 00:31:44,467
Luckily, she was my bestfriend, but she was no saint.

494
00:31:44,598 --> 00:31:48,732
She liked two things in life,and used one to get the other--

495
00:31:48,863 --> 00:31:53,302
money and men, and in
no particular order.

496
00:31:53,433 --> 00:31:55,957
Really?

497
00:31:56,088 --> 00:31:59,091
But she always
came back to Blain

498
00:31:59,221 --> 00:32:03,138
before and after her marriage.

499
00:32:03,269 --> 00:32:04,139
Why did he marry her?

500
00:32:07,229 --> 00:32:10,580
Because he loved her.

501
00:32:10,711 --> 00:32:13,192
She really was quite beautiful.

502
00:32:13,322 --> 00:32:15,672
[rumbling]

503
00:32:15,803 --> 00:32:18,197
That didn't take long.

504
00:32:18,327 --> 00:32:19,198
[music playing]

505
00:32:19,328 --> 00:32:23,158
[glass shattering]

506
00:32:23,289 --> 00:32:24,638
[shouting]

507
00:32:30,731 --> 00:32:32,124
Stop!

508
00:32:32,254 --> 00:32:34,126
Stop it!

509
00:32:34,256 --> 00:32:35,083
Stop it.

510
00:32:40,697 --> 00:32:42,047
[crying]

511
00:32:50,185 --> 00:32:52,535
I'm going to call it a night.

512
00:33:02,676 --> 00:33:03,459
Andy?

513
00:33:40,235 --> 00:33:42,063
[door creaking]

514
00:33:49,288 --> 00:33:51,203
Andy, is that you?

515
00:34:16,793 --> 00:34:18,143
[crying]

516
00:34:21,407 --> 00:34:22,147
Andy.

517
00:34:29,763 --> 00:34:33,114
Oh, Andy.

518
00:34:36,291 --> 00:34:37,640
Mommy.

519
00:34:37,771 --> 00:34:39,164
Oh, it's OK.

520
00:34:39,294 --> 00:34:40,643
It's OK, darling.

521
00:34:50,740 --> 00:34:51,611
It's OK.

522
00:34:55,267 --> 00:34:58,574
[music playing]

523
00:35:14,329 --> 00:35:16,070
Did my father kill my mother?

524
00:35:20,292 --> 00:35:22,032
I don't think he could
do a thing like that.

525
00:35:26,646 --> 00:35:29,475
So you're not leaving then?

526
00:35:29,605 --> 00:35:31,259
No.

527
00:35:31,390 --> 00:35:34,306
I told you I'm going to stay.

528
00:35:34,436 --> 00:35:37,135
Besides, I quite like it here.

529
00:35:40,964 --> 00:35:43,663
You're not scared of her?

530
00:35:43,793 --> 00:35:47,884
Andy, there's no ghost.

531
00:35:48,015 --> 00:35:52,367
Now sleep tight.

532
00:35:52,498 --> 00:35:54,108
Don't that the bed bugs bite.

533
00:35:54,239 --> 00:35:56,023
If they do, hit
them with your shoe.

534
00:36:00,549 --> 00:36:03,335
I'm sorry.

535
00:36:03,465 --> 00:36:05,293
For what?

536
00:36:05,424 --> 00:36:08,340
For scaring you.

537
00:36:08,470 --> 00:36:10,385
I made your window crash open.

538
00:36:14,694 --> 00:36:16,217
You did that?

539
00:36:16,348 --> 00:36:17,218
Yeah.

540
00:36:17,349 --> 00:36:19,655
How did you do that?

541
00:36:19,786 --> 00:36:21,396
I can't tell
you because you'll

542
00:36:21,527 --> 00:36:23,920
tell all the other nannies,and then it won't work anymore

543
00:36:24,051 --> 00:36:25,574
because they won't be scared.

544
00:36:25,705 --> 00:36:27,141
Oh, you can't
tell me, can you?

545
00:36:27,272 --> 00:36:30,579
Well, I think I'm just goingto tickle you until you

546
00:36:30,710 --> 00:36:33,147
tell me exactly how you did it.

547
00:36:33,278 --> 00:36:34,235
[laughter]
Do you give up?

548
00:36:34,366 --> 00:36:35,410
Do you give up?
Do you give up?

549
00:36:35,541 --> 00:36:37,020
- Yes, yes, yes.
- OK, tell me how.

550
00:36:37,151 --> 00:36:38,326
Don't tickle me.

551
00:36:38,457 --> 00:36:40,372
I've put magnets in
the window frames,

552
00:36:40,502 --> 00:36:43,723
and I used a massive
electromagnetic pulse

553
00:36:43,853 --> 00:36:45,246
to open and close the windows.

554
00:36:45,377 --> 00:36:47,596
Not an electromagnetic pulse.

555
00:36:47,727 --> 00:36:48,641
No, no, no.

556
00:36:48,771 --> 00:36:50,295
Oh, my God, you're so clever.

557
00:36:50,425 --> 00:36:51,209
Go to sleep.

558
00:36:51,339 --> 00:36:53,472
[laughter]

559
00:36:53,602 --> 00:36:54,429
Night night.

560
00:36:54,560 --> 00:36:55,387
See you in the morning.

561
00:36:55,517 --> 00:36:57,998
Good night, Liz.

562
00:36:58,128 --> 00:36:59,913
Good night, Andy.

563
00:37:05,962 --> 00:37:09,314
[music playing]

564
00:37:17,409 --> 00:37:19,715
[gunshot]

565
00:37:24,329 --> 00:37:27,680
[clock chiming]

566
00:37:44,697 --> 00:37:45,524
[rustling]

567
00:37:46,568 --> 00:37:49,049
Who's that?

568
00:37:49,179 --> 00:37:50,137
Sorry.

569
00:37:50,268 --> 00:37:51,225
I fell asleep.

570
00:37:51,356 --> 00:37:52,966
I'm going.

571
00:37:53,096 --> 00:37:53,880
Is Andrew all right?

572
00:37:57,492 --> 00:37:59,842
Well, he was very upset.

573
00:37:59,973 --> 00:38:00,887
He's asleep now.

574
00:38:04,891 --> 00:38:11,201
Look, I'm very sorryabout that scene in there.

575
00:38:11,332 --> 00:38:16,163
My brother and I have
some unresolved issues.

576
00:38:16,294 --> 00:38:18,687
It must all seem
pretty pathetic.

577
00:38:21,777 --> 00:38:24,519
Dr. Keaton, may I?

578
00:38:30,003 --> 00:38:34,094
I think you should know
tonight, Andy asked

579
00:38:34,224 --> 00:38:37,924
me if you murdered his mother.

580
00:38:38,054 --> 00:38:39,447
Did he?

581
00:38:39,578 --> 00:38:43,669
Well, I said I
didn't think so, but--

582
00:38:43,799 --> 00:38:45,671
I appreciate the
vote of confidence.

583
00:38:50,153 --> 00:38:54,419
I keep trying to
find the liar in you,

584
00:38:54,549 --> 00:38:56,159
but I just don't see it.

585
00:38:56,290 --> 00:38:58,553
Really?

586
00:38:58,684 --> 00:39:01,948
You're one of the
few that doesn't.

587
00:39:02,078 --> 00:39:03,645
I was lucky
enough to be married

588
00:39:03,776 --> 00:39:05,952
to a man who didn't lie.

589
00:39:06,082 --> 00:39:09,259
So I think I know
what to look for.

590
00:39:09,390 --> 00:39:12,828
I didn't know that
you were married.

591
00:39:12,959 --> 00:39:15,701
You never asked.

592
00:39:15,831 --> 00:39:18,399
Are you still married?

593
00:39:18,530 --> 00:39:19,792
No.

594
00:39:19,922 --> 00:39:21,141
He died.

595
00:39:21,271 --> 00:39:22,055
I'm sorry.

596
00:39:25,580 --> 00:39:27,800
I'm becoming a little clumsy.

597
00:39:27,930 --> 00:39:28,670
That's OK.

598
00:39:31,456 --> 00:39:33,501
I don't understand you.

599
00:39:33,632 --> 00:39:36,852
Now he's such a
wonderful little boy.

600
00:39:36,983 --> 00:39:38,114
He's bright.

601
00:39:38,245 --> 00:39:40,813
He's sensitive.

602
00:39:40,943 --> 00:39:43,598
Why do you keep
pushing him away?

603
00:39:43,729 --> 00:39:45,078
I provide him witheverything that he needs,

604
00:39:45,208 --> 00:39:47,428
the best that money can buy.

605
00:39:47,559 --> 00:39:50,605
Yeah, but he needs
love and affection.

606
00:39:53,956 --> 00:39:54,783
That's what I hired you for.

607
00:39:57,699 --> 00:40:00,180
Doesn't it bother you?

608
00:40:00,310 --> 00:40:01,137
He's your son.

609
00:40:04,706 --> 00:40:10,451
I provide for him,
but he is not my son.

610
00:40:10,582 --> 00:40:13,802
[music playing]

611
00:40:20,766 --> 00:40:22,071
Andy, are you ready?

612
00:40:22,202 --> 00:40:23,203
[knocking on door]
Come on.

613
00:40:23,333 --> 00:40:24,117
Let's go.

614
00:40:26,685 --> 00:40:29,992
You can't go on a picnic
dressed like that.

615
00:40:30,123 --> 00:40:31,820
I can dress any way I want.

616
00:40:31,951 --> 00:40:33,213
You do.

617
00:40:33,343 --> 00:40:36,695
I dress appropriately,
and so should you.

618
00:40:36,825 --> 00:40:38,914
Put on your jeans and sneakers.

619
00:40:39,045 --> 00:40:43,397
All right, on conditionthat you wear your uniform,

620
00:40:43,528 --> 00:40:44,877
and don't forget the tie.

621
00:40:48,794 --> 00:40:50,622
ELIZABETH GUINNESS: You'll
have to help me, OK?

622
00:40:50,752 --> 00:40:52,537
One, two, three.

623
00:40:57,150 --> 00:40:58,978
Get some stuff out of here.

624
00:41:03,069 --> 00:41:06,376
[horses neighing]

625
00:41:10,990 --> 00:41:12,644
Well, well.

626
00:41:12,774 --> 00:41:14,515
And I thought you were going tobe working on your manuscript

627
00:41:14,646 --> 00:41:15,777
this afternoon.

628
00:41:15,908 --> 00:41:16,865
Well, Jillian
convinced me that it'd

629
00:41:16,996 --> 00:41:18,258
be more fun to go riding.

630
00:41:18,388 --> 00:41:19,955
Yeah, fun.

631
00:41:20,086 --> 00:41:23,045
The story of your life, Blain.

632
00:41:23,176 --> 00:41:25,004
You could lighten up a
little bit, big brother.

633
00:41:25,134 --> 00:41:27,006
RICHARD KEATON: Go to hell.

634
00:41:27,136 --> 00:41:28,964
[horses neighing]

635
00:41:30,357 --> 00:41:32,098
Just, just further
than the real--

636
00:41:32,228 --> 00:41:34,970
Andy, it's your father.

637
00:41:35,101 --> 00:41:36,711
Hi.

638
00:41:36,842 --> 00:41:38,931
Hello there.

639
00:41:39,061 --> 00:41:40,323
ANDREW KEATON: Hi.

640
00:41:40,454 --> 00:41:44,240
I see we're playing
truant this afternoon.

641
00:41:44,371 --> 00:41:48,027
And you, Ms. Guinness,are looking very official.

642
00:41:48,157 --> 00:41:52,771
Well, I lost a
negotiated settlement.

643
00:41:52,901 --> 00:41:55,425
It's a one-time-only event.

644
00:41:55,556 --> 00:41:57,689
This is good.
May I join you?

645
00:41:57,819 --> 00:41:58,516
Oh, sure.

646
00:42:02,215 --> 00:42:08,351
Andrew, I'm very sorry forwhat happened last night.

647
00:42:08,482 --> 00:42:10,179
How come you and uncle
Blain always fight?

648
00:42:13,792 --> 00:42:17,230
Andy, why don't
you tell your father

649
00:42:17,360 --> 00:42:18,231
what you were just telling me?

650
00:42:21,321 --> 00:42:24,106
Well go on, Andy.

651
00:42:24,237 --> 00:42:29,459
Well, what I was
saying was at the moment

652
00:42:29,590 --> 00:42:31,592
that the black hole
is formed, time

653
00:42:31,723 --> 00:42:33,812
freezes on the event horizon.

654
00:42:33,942 --> 00:42:35,465
And the last photons
of light that

655
00:42:35,596 --> 00:42:38,207
escape after the
black hole is formed

656
00:42:38,338 --> 00:42:39,992
are frozen in that moment.

657
00:42:40,122 --> 00:42:42,734
It's not on the
event horizon, Andy.

658
00:42:42,864 --> 00:42:45,824
It's an infinitesimal
distance above it.

659
00:42:45,954 --> 00:42:47,782
You wouldn't detect
time-frozen photons

660
00:42:47,913 --> 00:42:50,350
if they were at the horizon.

661
00:42:50,480 --> 00:42:52,004
Well, why don't--

662
00:42:52,134 --> 00:42:53,527
why don't you explain thedifference to us so we know.

663
00:42:53,658 --> 00:42:55,137
Well you have to understandthere are no margins

664
00:42:55,268 --> 00:42:56,356
for imprecision in science.

665
00:43:02,101 --> 00:43:02,971
Andy.

666
00:43:03,102 --> 00:43:03,929
Andy.

667
00:43:04,059 --> 00:43:05,191
Don't call me that.

668
00:43:05,321 --> 00:43:06,845
Only Liz can call me Andy.

669
00:43:06,975 --> 00:43:07,802
Only Liz!

670
00:43:11,937 --> 00:43:13,678
Why did you bother
to come out here?

671
00:43:16,637 --> 00:43:18,465
I was curious.

672
00:43:18,596 --> 00:43:20,119
I couldn't imagine Andy--

673
00:43:20,249 --> 00:43:23,035
Andrew, enjoying all this.

674
00:43:23,165 --> 00:43:24,689
You were curious.

675
00:43:24,819 --> 00:43:28,388
Well he is a child, and heneeds to learn how to play,

676
00:43:28,518 --> 00:43:32,740
how to enjoy
sentiment and emotion.

677
00:43:32,871 --> 00:43:37,789
Ms. Guinness, it seems thatyou are a bit of a romantic.

678
00:43:37,919 --> 00:43:39,529
What is that supposed to mean?

679
00:43:39,660 --> 00:43:42,532
It means that logic and reasonplay no part in your makeup.

680
00:43:42,663 --> 00:43:44,230
Well, that's ridiculous.

681
00:43:44,360 --> 00:43:47,189
I'm the most logical
person that I know.

682
00:43:47,320 --> 00:43:50,192
I'm sorry if I
ruined your picnic.

683
00:43:50,323 --> 00:43:51,106
He has to learn.

684
00:43:57,112 --> 00:44:00,333
[music playing]

685
00:44:05,381 --> 00:44:11,387
Dr. Keaton, you
go to him, please.

686
00:44:11,518 --> 00:44:14,173
Just make it up to him.

687
00:44:14,303 --> 00:44:16,392
Invite him to your lab tomorrow.

688
00:44:16,523 --> 00:44:19,004
It doesn't have to be for long.

689
00:44:19,134 --> 00:44:22,921
I know he'd love
to see you working.

690
00:44:23,051 --> 00:44:23,791
Please.

691
00:44:29,231 --> 00:44:33,322
I don't know how you can
say he's not your son.

692
00:44:33,453 --> 00:44:34,846
You're exactly like him.

693
00:44:44,638 --> 00:44:45,639
Pretty picture,
don't you think?

694
00:45:25,461 --> 00:45:28,769
[thunder]

695
00:45:34,906 --> 00:45:35,733
Damn.

696
00:45:39,345 --> 00:45:40,694
[screaming]

697
00:45:44,306 --> 00:45:46,744
Liz!

698
00:45:46,874 --> 00:45:47,657
Liz?

699
00:45:47,788 --> 00:45:48,833
Liz, wake up.

700
00:45:48,963 --> 00:45:51,226
Come on.

701
00:45:51,357 --> 00:45:54,360
She's at my window and
she wants to come in.

702
00:45:54,490 --> 00:45:56,710
The lights won't go on.

703
00:45:56,841 --> 00:45:57,972
What time is it?

704
00:45:58,103 --> 00:45:59,539
It's 17 minutes after 3:00.

705
00:45:59,669 --> 00:46:00,540
[screams]

706
00:46:00,670 --> 00:46:01,410
ELIZABETH GUINNESS: It's OK.

707
00:46:01,541 --> 00:46:02,411
Let me get a flashlight.

708
00:46:02,542 --> 00:46:03,325
It's OK.

709
00:46:03,456 --> 00:46:06,415
Come on.

710
00:46:06,546 --> 00:46:07,939
It's OK.

711
00:46:08,069 --> 00:46:10,506
Come on.

712
00:46:10,637 --> 00:46:11,464
[thunder]

713
00:46:11,594 --> 00:46:14,380
ANDREW KEATON: That's her!

714
00:46:14,510 --> 00:46:15,860
Stay here.

715
00:46:23,041 --> 00:46:24,216
[screams]

716
00:46:25,304 --> 00:46:26,087
It's just a tree.

717
00:46:29,134 --> 00:46:29,961
It's OK.

718
00:46:30,091 --> 00:46:32,398
It's OK.

719
00:46:32,528 --> 00:46:35,967
There really aren't
any ghosts, Andy.

720
00:46:36,097 --> 00:46:38,926
Andy, are you all right?

721
00:46:39,057 --> 00:46:41,276
There was a tree
tapping at the window.

722
00:46:41,407 --> 00:46:42,843
Yeah, power's off
in the whole house.

723
00:46:42,974 --> 00:46:45,237
Oh.

724
00:46:45,367 --> 00:46:49,632
Well, why don't we go
down to the library?

725
00:46:49,763 --> 00:46:51,809
At least we know
there's a fire there.

726
00:46:51,939 --> 00:46:54,289
Yeah, why not?

727
00:46:54,420 --> 00:46:56,161
Can't work like this anyway.

728
00:46:56,291 --> 00:46:57,510
Good.

729
00:46:57,640 --> 00:46:59,164
I'll go and put on a robe.

730
00:46:59,294 --> 00:47:00,034
I'll see you down there.

731
00:47:00,165 --> 00:47:00,905
OK.

732
00:47:07,999 --> 00:47:08,826
[whimpers]

733
00:47:11,916 --> 00:47:13,743
Can we go now?

734
00:47:13,874 --> 00:47:15,571
Are you still scared?

735
00:47:15,702 --> 00:47:17,443
No.

736
00:47:17,573 --> 00:47:18,357
Good.

737
00:47:18,487 --> 00:47:19,227
Let's go.

738
00:47:46,820 --> 00:47:49,040
Have you been
awake all this time?

739
00:47:49,170 --> 00:47:49,910
You snore.

740
00:47:53,522 --> 00:47:54,306
I do not.

741
00:47:57,483 --> 00:47:58,179
It's very relaxing.

742
00:48:02,009 --> 00:48:02,749
Power's back on.

743
00:48:05,839 --> 00:48:07,667
Do you think you couldcarry him up to his room?

744
00:48:11,801 --> 00:48:13,760
Every father should
try it at least once.

745
00:48:51,102 --> 00:48:51,885
Richard.

746
00:49:00,894 --> 00:49:03,766
Thanks.

747
00:49:03,897 --> 00:49:06,769
For what?

748
00:49:06,900 --> 00:49:11,339
For coming to see
why he screamed,

749
00:49:11,470 --> 00:49:15,822
for carrying him upstairs.He won't forget.

750
00:49:18,520 --> 00:49:20,479
He was asleep.

751
00:49:20,609 --> 00:49:21,959
No, he wasn't.

752
00:49:28,139 --> 00:49:28,966
Good night.

753
00:49:34,101 --> 00:49:37,409
[music playing]

754
00:50:02,956 --> 00:50:03,826
No, I can't.

755
00:50:13,923 --> 00:50:16,796
I'm sorry.

756
00:50:16,926 --> 00:50:19,755
I can't.

757
00:50:19,886 --> 00:50:21,757
I'm sorry I--

758
00:50:21,888 --> 00:50:24,760
I have to be sure.

759
00:50:24,891 --> 00:50:27,807
Of what?

760
00:50:27,937 --> 00:50:30,723
Whether or not I killed my wife?

761
00:50:30,853 --> 00:50:33,639
I wasn't even
thinking about that.

762
00:50:33,769 --> 00:50:35,075
What then?

763
00:50:38,252 --> 00:50:44,911
What you have to understand isI've known real love, Richard,

764
00:50:45,042 --> 00:50:47,435
and I won't settle
for anything less.

765
00:50:47,566 --> 00:50:48,306
I can't.

766
00:50:51,961 --> 00:50:52,788
I'm sorry.

767
00:51:36,180 --> 00:51:37,050
[music playing]

768
00:51:37,181 --> 00:51:38,530
[horses neighing]

769
00:52:08,342 --> 00:52:09,909
Thank you.

770
00:52:10,039 --> 00:52:12,085
Maybe I'd better
saddle up Augustine.

771
00:52:12,216 --> 00:52:14,000
Amber doesn't like
strangers much.

772
00:52:14,131 --> 00:52:15,523
ELIZABETH GUINNESS: Oh,
she'll be all right.

773
00:52:15,654 --> 00:52:17,873
I'll just change
into my riding gear.

774
00:52:18,004 --> 00:52:18,831
Thank you.

775
00:52:37,763 --> 00:52:41,114
You're very brave
taking Amber for a ride.

776
00:52:41,245 --> 00:52:43,421
Alycia was scared stiff of her.

777
00:52:43,551 --> 00:52:44,335
Thanks.

778
00:52:47,555 --> 00:52:49,992
Poor Andy.

779
00:52:50,123 --> 00:52:51,342
Can't say I'm surprised.

780
00:52:51,472 --> 00:52:53,735
He has scared off
three other nannies.

781
00:52:53,866 --> 00:52:56,129
So you think he did it?

782
00:52:56,260 --> 00:52:57,696
Of course he did.

783
00:52:57,826 --> 00:52:59,176
Why would you think otherwise?

784
00:52:59,306 --> 00:53:00,133
I don't know.

785
00:53:00,264 --> 00:53:03,136
It just seems really odd.

786
00:53:03,267 --> 00:53:04,703
I thought we were
really getting along.

787
00:53:07,880 --> 00:53:09,186
Have you told
Richard about it?

788
00:53:09,316 --> 00:53:10,099
No.

789
00:53:10,230 --> 00:53:11,362
No, not yet.

790
00:53:11,492 --> 00:53:14,191
I want to work it
through with Andy.

791
00:53:19,805 --> 00:53:21,676
[horse neighing]

792
00:53:24,766 --> 00:53:25,593
Be careful.

793
00:53:25,724 --> 00:53:27,160
She's a sly one.

794
00:53:27,291 --> 00:53:29,554
Alycia's the only one
she ever let ride her.

795
00:53:29,684 --> 00:53:32,644
I think I'll be OK.

796
00:53:32,774 --> 00:53:34,602
So where's Andy?

797
00:53:34,733 --> 00:53:36,430
He's with his
father in the lab.

798
00:53:36,561 --> 00:53:37,344
Oh, really?

799
00:53:37,475 --> 00:53:38,519
Mhmm.

800
00:53:38,650 --> 00:53:40,217
They're making progress.

801
00:53:40,347 --> 00:53:42,306
You're quite the
nanny, aren't you?

802
00:53:42,436 --> 00:53:45,744
Are you off somewhere?

803
00:53:45,874 --> 00:53:47,049
Off to plead for
another deadline

804
00:53:47,180 --> 00:53:48,921
extension on my manuscript.

805
00:53:49,051 --> 00:53:51,010
Or if not, to sell my car.

806
00:53:51,140 --> 00:53:53,665
You'd sell your car?

807
00:53:53,795 --> 00:53:55,362
Actually, no.

808
00:53:55,493 --> 00:53:57,451
I think I'd rather be the onlyhomeless person in America

809
00:53:57,582 --> 00:54:00,149
sleeping in a 1924 Darracq.

810
00:54:00,280 --> 00:54:01,760
I don't understand
how you can be broke.

811
00:54:01,890 --> 00:54:05,981
I mean, you seem to be
doing pretty well to me.

812
00:54:06,112 --> 00:54:10,682
Yes, well appearances
can be deceiving.

813
00:54:10,812 --> 00:54:13,946
Blain, I am--

814
00:54:14,076 --> 00:54:16,165
I don't know what you
make of this, but I--

815
00:54:16,296 --> 00:54:17,297
I found it in my room.

816
00:54:20,082 --> 00:54:21,954
You don't belong here,
so you'd better leave.

817
00:54:22,084 --> 00:54:23,869
Alycia.

818
00:54:23,999 --> 00:54:26,263
Do you think Andy wrote it?

819
00:54:26,393 --> 00:54:27,525
Well, I think
that we can be quite

820
00:54:27,655 --> 00:54:28,526
certain that Alycia didn't.

821
00:54:28,656 --> 00:54:31,224
That's for sure.

822
00:54:31,355 --> 00:54:33,487
Did he do this sort of thingwith the previous nannies?

823
00:54:33,618 --> 00:54:34,793
